We can “build” the liabilities‐and–owners equity number by “starting” with the capital that is introduced at the very start (that is, all three “Initial20231231001” rows add up to 3,000,000 + 5,000,000 + 5,000,000 = 13,000,000) and then “adjust” that number by adding in the net income earned during the period. (This net income is “given” by the aggregate profit amounts that appear on every “Sale” row; in our example the sale lines’ profit amounts add up roughly to 1,602,500.30.) 

Thus, when no other items are “separately” added or subtracted from the liabilities‐and–owners equity section—and since many transactions (such as purchases that are “paid” or “unpaid,” expense, transfers, etc.) already have been “net‐effected” in the operating outcome—the final balance is computed as

  Final Liabilities and Owners Equity = Initial capital + net profit 
              = 13,000,000.00 + 1,602,500.30 
              ≈ 14,602,500.30

That is we say:

• Total Liabilities and Owners Equity Initial Value = 13,000,000.00  
• Total Liabilities and Owners Equity End Value = 14,602,500.30
